'''State-sponsored internet sockpuppetry''' is a government's use of paid internet propagandists with the intention of swaying online opinion, undermining dissident communities, or changing the perception of what is the dominant view (often via [[astroturfing]]).{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}{{neologism inline|date=March 2017}}
The following is a list of the known or alleged examples of state-sponsored Internet [[propaganda]]:
==[[Asia-Pacific]]== *{{flag|China}}: [[Internet Water Army]], [[50 Cent Party]], in operation since October 2004 *{{flag|Myanmar}}: the [[Tatmadaw]] and the Burmese Government has sponsored propaganda through Internet and dismiss its atrocities towards its minorities like the [[Rohingya people|Rohingya]], [[Shan people|Shan]], [[Kachin people|Kachin]] and [[Karen people]].<ref>http://factsanddetails.com/southeast-asia/Myanmar/sub5_5e/entry-3095.html</ref><ref>https://coconuts.co/yangon/features/myanmar-times-editor-admit-producing-propaganda/</ref> *{{flag|North Korea}}: the troll army of North Korea, which is known to be supportive for the [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)|Kim dynasty]]'s rule, and put anti-South Korean, anti-American and pro-North Korean regime. They first appeared in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mike Firn|website=The Telegraph|date=13 August 2013 |title=North Korea builds online troll army of 3,000|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10239283/North-Korea-builds-online-troll-army-of-3000.html}}</ref> *{{flag|Philippines}}: The [[Oxford University]] released a study claiming that hired "keyboard trolls" played a role in President [[Rodrigo Duterte]]'s [[Rodrigo Duterte presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign in 2016]]. The study said that the Duterte campaign team spent at least $200 thousand and hired 400 to 500 people to defend Duterte from online critics. It also added that the hired "trolls" remain to support Duterte and his administration after he was elected. Online trolls were allegedly used by the administration to silence critics through threats of violence and rape to people critical to Duterte's policies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Duterte: No money for trolls, rigged surveys|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/24/17/duterte-no-money-for-trolls-rigged-surveys|accessdate=30 October 2017|work=ABS-CBN News|date=24 June 2017}}</ref> Duterte, while admitted to paying people to support him online during the elections said he has followers referring to his staunch supporter, [[Mocha Uson]] who runs the support group [[Mocha Uson Blog]] but insists that Uson offers her services free.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Valente|first1=Catherine|title=Duterte on use of ‘troll’ army: I have followers|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/duterte-on-use-of-troll-army-i-have-followers/340560/|accessdate=30 October 2017|work=The Manila Times|date=25 July 2017}}</ref> *{{flag|Singapore}}: ::1. Ruling party [[People's Action Party]] and its youth wing [[Young PAP]] have been officially reported to have organized teams to work both publicly and anonymously to counter criticism of party and government in cyberspace since 1995.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/1995/07/updata-41/|title=Mickey Unbound|last=|first=|date=1995-07-01|work=WIRED|access-date=2017-08-25|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|issue=1.4|page=51|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodan|first=Garry|date=1998-03-01|title=The Internet and Political Control in Singapore|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.2307/2657651/abstract|journal=Political Science Quarterly|language=en|volume=113|issue=1|pages=63–89|doi=10.2307/2657651|issn=1538-165X|archive-url=http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/apcity/unpan002726.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-25|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Internet world watches as Young PAP enters cyberspace|last=Chen|first=Tommi|date=14 March 1995|work=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tesoro|first1=Jose Manuel|title=The Great Online Debate|url=http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/96/1011/feat1.html|work=Asiaweek|date=11 October 1996}}</ref> As reported by the Straits Times, as of 2007, the group consists of two teams, led by members of parliament of [[People's Action Party]], where one team strategises the campaign the other team executes the strategies.<ref>{{cite news|author=Li Xueying|website=The Straits Times|title=PAP moves to counter criticism of party, Govt in cyberspace|date=3 February 2007}}</ref> ::2. There are also pro-party individuals known as 'Internet Brigade'<ref>{{cite news|author=Seah Chiang Nee|website=The Star|date=24 November 2012 |title=PAP’s quiet counter-insurgency|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/opinion/columnists/insight-down-south/2012/11/24/paps-quiet-counterinsurgency/}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Koh|first1=Gillian|title=Singapore Perspectives 2013: Governance|date=2014|publisher=World Scientific Pub. Co.|location=Singapore|isbn=9789814520751|page=56}}</ref> who claim to be not affiliated with the party nor officially endorsed by party, who setup elaborate social media and web page to 'defend' the ruling party of online chatters and to criticize social-political websites critical of the government and members of opposition parties. They have information about their party's endorsed candidate personal details and events not publicly known and MP elected as their members, Often they have anonymous members, sometimes with fake or purchased identity, re-posting on Internet forums and social-media their published articles<ref>{{cite news|author=Leonard Lim|website=The Straits Times|title=Netizens setup Facebook page to defend PAP, Govt in cyberspace|date=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Pearl Lee|website=The Straits Times|title=Supporters seek to amplify PAP voice online|date=20 September 2015|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/politics/supporters-seek-to-amplify-pap-voice-online}}</ref> ::3. The [[Ministry of Communications and Information]] manages an official government website, Factually, which claims to provide facts to counter false accusations online and addresses assertions related to the government and People's Action Party politicians.<ref>{{cite news|title=Factually website clarifies 'widespread' falsehoods|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/factually-website-clarifies-widespread-falsehoods|work=The Straits Times|date=2 March 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Henson|first1=Bertha|title=Factually, the G website, is a shambles|url=http://themiddleground.sg/2017/04/16/factually-g-website-shambles/|work=The Middle Ground|date=16 April 2017}}</ref> It also provides justifications for government tariff raises, denial of consumer tax raises,<ref>{{cite news|title=S’pore govt said it was not planning to raise GST after 2015 General Election|url=https://mothership.sg/2017/11/when-will-singapore-raise-gst/|work=Mothership.sg}}</ref> and explanations for controversial government decisions such as the spending of $880,000 on a rubbish bin centre.<ref>{{cite news|title=$470,000 bin centre was a ‘complex and complicated’ project: Singapore’s arts council|url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/470000-bin-centre-was-complex-and-complicated-105003322.html|language=English}}</ref> ::4. The [[Info-communications Media Development Authority]] (IMDA) frequently engages advertising agencies to promote civic campaigns and national day celebrations on traditional media, video-sharing websites and social media.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tay|first1=Vivienne|title=Massive government tender sees 30 agencies added to roster|url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/massive-government-tender-sees-30-agencies-added-to-roster/|website=Marketing Interactive}}</ref> Some of these [[nation-building]] efforts are seen as selective in choosing the historical narratives, often highlighting the achievements of the ruling party,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tan|first1=Kenneth Paul|title=Choosing What to Remember in Neoliberal Singapore: The Singapore Story, State Censorship and State-Sponsored Nostalgia|journal=Asian Studies Review|date=10 April 2016|volume=40|issue=2|pages=231–249|doi=10.1080/10357823.2016.1158779}}</ref> resulting in a collective amnesia of the country's political history.<ref>{{cite news|title=A new generation rewrites history, doubts Singapore's vulnerability|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/a-new-generation-rewrites-history-doubts-singapores-vulnerability|work=The Straits Times|date=30 January 2015|language=en}}</ref> *{{flag|Vietnam}}: [[Public opinion brigades]].<ref>{{citation|title=Vietnam admits deploying bloggers to support government|author=Nga Pham|date=12 January 2013|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-20982985}}</ref> As of 2017, the military currently employs at least 10,000 members in a special force, named [[Force 47]], to counter criticisms of the government in cyberspace<ref>{{cite news|title=Vietnam has 10,000-strong ‘cyber troop’: general - Tuoi Tre News|url=https://tuoitrenews.vn/news/politics/20171226/vietnam-has-10000strong-cyber-troop-general/43326.html|work=Tuoi Tre News|date=26 December 2017|language=vi-VN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Vietnam censors to fight 'internet chaos'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-42494113|work=BBC News|date=27 December 2017}}</ref> and hacking into dissident anti-government websites and installing [[spyware]] to [[Website visitor tracking|track visitors]]<ref name="Hookway">{{cite news|last1=Hookway|first1=James|title=Introducing Force 47, Vietnam’s New Weapon Against Online Dissent|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/introducing-force-47-vietnams-new-weapon-against-online-dissent-1514721606|accessdate=3 January 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|agency=Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Company, Inc.|date=31 December 2017}}</ref>.
==[[MENA|Middle East and North Africa]]== *{{flag|Iran}}: Islamic Republic's troll army, known to be supportive for [[Ayatollah Khomeini]] and the Khomeini rule, and also criticizing any attempts that against the rule of the [[Khomeini family]].<ref>http://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2018/01/17/ANALYSIS-Unveiling-Iranian-pro-government-trolls-and-cyber-warriors.html</ref> *{{flag|Israel}}: ::1. [[Hasbara]], which means "explanation" in Hebrew, is also a euphemism for the public relations efforts to disseminate abroad positive information or propaganda about the State of Israel and its actions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benedictus|first1=Leo|title=Invasion of the troll armies: ‘Social media where the war goes on’|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/nov/06/troll-armies-social-media-trump-russian|work=The Guardian|date=6 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Government to use citizens as army in social media war|url=http://www.jpost.com/Diplomacy-and-Politics/Government-to-use-citizens-as-army-in-social-media-war-322972|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=14 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Israel to pay students to defend it online|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/08/14/israel-students-social-media/2651715/|work=USA Today|date=14 August 2013|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Matthew|title=Israeli propaganda war hits social media|url=http://www.smh.com.au/it-pro/government-it/israeli-propaganda-war-hits-social-media-20140717-ztvky.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=18 July 2014}}</ref> ::2. [[Jewish Internet Defense Force]] *{{flag|Morocco}}: the Moroccan Government has been sponsoring and funding propaganda as well as establishment of sockpuppets around<ref>http://globalmonitoringcenter.com/33667/284053/a/afrol-news-apologises-for-publishing-moroccan-propaganda</ref> to undermine [[Algeria]]'s territorial integrity, promoting separatism against [[Spain]], as well as promoting anti-[[Western Sahara]]n independence issue and deny its poor treatments towards [[Riffian people]].<ref>https://www.pambazuka.org/governance/western-sahara-kidnappings-unpacking-moroccan-propaganda</ref><ref>http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/7109/moroccan-state-propaganda-and-the-western-saharan-</ref><ref>http://www.wsrw.org/a105x3649</ref> The [[Morocco World News]] is sometimes accused to be another propaganda outlet of the Moroccan Government and posting unrealistic news. *{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}: King's Brigade, known to be supportive for the [[Saud family]] and the monarchy. Its mission is to denounce any criticisms against the Saud family, and praising [[Sharia Law]]. *{{flag|Sudan}}: the Government of Sudan has been accused for using propaganda penetrating the reality, notably during the [[War in Darfur|Darfur War]], by labelling the non-Arab Darfuris as heretics and enemy of Sudan, to increase the level of massacre and genocide.<ref>http://africanarguments.org/2010/07/28/ideology-of-hatred-in-a-brokered-state/</ref> It was believed to be the similar propaganda tactics used by Khartoum over the [[South Sudan]] question, notably [[Abyei]] problem.<ref>https://radiotamazuj.org/en/news/article/deng-alor-says-inclusion-of-abyei-in-sudanese-elections-is-propaganda</ref> *{{flag|Turkey}}: 6.000 paid social media commentators known as "[[AK Trolls]]" mainly spreading pro-Erdogan propaganda and attack those opposing [[Recep Tayyip Erdoğan|Erdogan]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/nov/06/troll-armies-social-media-trump-russian</ref>
==[[Europe]]== *{{flag|Russia}}: ::1. [[Web brigades]] first alleged in April 2003 ::2. "CyberBerkut", Identified as "a front organization for Russian state-sponsored cyber activity, supporting Russia's military operations and strategic objectives in Ukraine"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dia.mil/Military-Power-Publications/|title=Military Power Publications|website=www.dia.mil|language=English|access-date=2017-09-25}}</ref> ::3. [[Internet Research Agency]], also known as "Trolls from Olgino". Identified as "trolling"/astroturfing company operating on numerous sites. *{{flag|United Kingdom}}: "Online Covert Action" and other missions by the [[Joint Threat Research Intelligence Group]], revealed by [[Edward Snowden]] in February 2014.<ref>Greenwald, Glenn and Andrew Fishman. [https://firstlook.org/theintercept/2015/06/22/controversial-gchq-unit-domestic-law-enforcement-propaganda/ Controversial GCHQ Unit Engaged in Domestic Law Enforcement, Online Propaganda, Psychology Research]. ''The Intercept''. 2015-06-22.</ref>
==[[Americas]]== *{{flag|United States}}: ::1. [[Center for Strategic Counterterrorism Communications]], founded in 2010.<ref>[https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/03/why-its-so-hard-to-stop-isis-propaganda/386216/ Why It's So Hard to Stop ISIS Propaganda]. ''The Atlantic''. 2015-03-02.</ref> ::2. [[Operation Earnest Voice]], officially started in 2011. *{{flag|Venezuela}}: [[Bolivarian Army of Trolls]], founded in 2017, is tasked with disseminating [[Bolivarian propaganda]] and spreading disinformation.
